Skip already-installed reverse deps in `InstallPlan.completed`.

When cabal-install marks a package as completed, it looks at its
reverse dependencies to find the ones that are now ready to build.
The filter only considers whether the rev-dep's direct deps are all
in the completed set — it doesn't check whether the rev-dep itself
is already `Installed` or `PreExisting`.

That's usually fine because an `Installed` package starts in the
`completedSet` and isn't in `processingSet`, so the caller never
actually processes it.  But the `completed` function still pulls it
into `newlyReady` and hands it to `asReadyPackage`, which throws
`internalError "completed" "not in configured state: Installed X"`.

This matters for haskell.nix v2 slicing: the slicer pre-populates
the cabal store with the v2 slices of a pkg's transitive deps, then
invokes `cabal v2-build` on a shim that pulls the target pkg in.
The re-solve finds the pre-installed units, marks them `Installed`,
and may produce a plan where a `Configured` package (that cabal has
to build inside the shim) has a `revDirectDep` of an already-
`Installed` one.  At completion time, cabal explodes.

Filtering `newlyReady` to `Configured{}` entries only keeps
`asReadyPackage`'s precondition honest without changing the build
semantics — the `Installed` entries were already in `completedSet`.

--- a/src/Distribution/Client/InstallPlan.hs
+++ b/src/Distribution/Client/InstallPlan.hs
@@ -727,10 +727,21 @@
   where
     completedSet' = Set.insert pkgid completedSet

-    -- each direct reverse dep where all direct deps are completed
+    -- each direct reverse dep where all direct deps are completed.
+    --
+    -- Skip reverse deps that are already Installed / PreExisting —
+    -- those aren't in `processingSet`, never will be, and there's
+    -- nothing to "mark ready" for them.  When a plan composes
+    -- pre-installed units (e.g. haskell.nix v2 slicing pre-populates
+    -- the cabal store with sliced deps), the re-solve may produce a
+    -- mixed Installed+Configured plan where a Configured package
+    -- reverse-depends on an already-Installed one; the default
+    -- filter would pull the Installed pkg into `newlyReady` and then
+    -- blow up in `asReadyPackage`.
     newlyReady =
       [ dep
       | dep <- revDirectDeps plan pkgid
+      , case dep of Configured{} -> True; _ -> False
       , all
           ((`Set.member` completedSet') . nodeKey)
           (directDeps plan (nodeKey dep))
